---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import SectionDivider from '../components/SectionDivider.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import SourceLink from '../components/SourceLink.astro';
import SourceList from '../components/SourceList.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    title: 'NSW Energy from Waste Infrastructure Plan',
    publisher: 'NSW Government',
    date: '2021',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'North Coast Region Waste Investment Report',
    publisher: 'NSW Government',
    date: '2020',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Stotts Creek organics (FOGO) processing facility',
    publisher: 'Tweed Shire Council',
    note: 'Largest organics facility in the Northern Rivers. URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Victorian ban on organics to landfill',
    publisher: 'Sustainability Victoria / EPA Victoria',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Centralised vs local: the model question"
  description="The Blakebrook debate is usually framed as a siting question. The more important question is the model: one big centralised landfill, many small local ones, or a networked, hierarchy-first system that treats landfill as the last resort."
  progress
  article
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="The model question"
    title="One big hole, many small ones, or a different model entirely"
  >
    This is the most important page, because it reframes the whole debate. The
    argument that matters is not <em>where</em> the landfill goes — it is
    whether a 50-year landfill commitment should be the starting point at all.
  </PageHeader>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 pb-8">
    <div class="prose-body mt-10">
      <SectionDivider>Model A</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Centralised — one big regional landfill</h2>
      <p>This is the Blakebrook-style approach.</p>
      <p><strong>In its favour:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>economies of scale;</li>
        <li>better engineering becomes affordable;</li>
        <li>a single regulatory point of accountability;</li>
        <li>
          leachate treatment plants and gas-to-energy become economic at scale;
        </li>
        <li>lower per-tonne cost.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Against:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>concentrated environmental impact on one community;</li>
        <li>long-haul truck movements from every member council;</li>
        <li>a single point of failure;</li>
        <li>a &ldquo;sacrifice zone&rdquo; dynamic;</li>
        <li>
          it locks in 50 years of landfilling as the default response to waste.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <SectionDivider>Model B</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Decentralised — each council manages its own</h2>
      <p><strong>In its favour:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>local accountability — each community sees its own waste;</li>
        <li>shorter transport distances;</li>
        <li>resilience through redundancy;</li>
        <li>a built-in incentive to reduce.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Against:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>smaller facilities can&rsquo;t afford the best engineering;</li>
        <li>more total land sterilised;</li>
        <li>duplicated infrastructure;</li>
        <li>harder to fund monitoring and staff.</li>
      </ul>

      <SectionDivider>Model C</SectionDivider>
      <h2>Networked + hierarchy-first — the model nobody&rsquo;s quite proposing</h2>
      <p>
        Modern best practice treats landfill as the <strong>last</strong>{' '}
        component of a waste system, not the first. The hierarchy runs:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Avoid and reduce</strong> — container deposit scheme
          expansion, product stewardship, single-use plastics policy.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Recover at source</strong> — three-bin kerbside is universal
          in the Northern Rivers, but FOGO (food and garden organics) recovery
          rates vary from roughly 30% to 70% by LGA. Closing that gap alone
          delays any need for new landfill capacity.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Process regionally</strong> — large-scale FOGO composting
          (Stotts Creek&rsquo;s organics facility is the largest in the Northern
          Rivers),<SourceLink n={3} /> construction-and-demolition recycling,
          and materials recovery. These <em>can</em> be centralised, because
          their outputs are products, not pollutants.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Residual treatment</strong> — energy-from-waste is on the
          table under the NSW Energy from Waste Infrastructure Plan 2021<SourceLink
            n={1}
          /> and the North Coast Region Waste Investment Report 2020.<SourceLink
            n={2}
          /> It is controversial, but a legitimate part of the conversation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Residual landfill</strong> — only after all of the above, at
          minimum scale, distributed across existing licensed sites.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <PullQuote>
      A 50-year landfill commitment today assumes 2075 looks like 2025.
      Mandatory product stewardship, expanded container deposits,
      energy-from-waste, advanced sorting, and bans on organics-to-landfill
      (already happening in Victoria) could halve residual waste within a
      decade. Building for 50 years of 2020s-volume residual waste is
      over-building.
    </PullQuote>

    <div class="prose-body">
      <p>
        None of this means &ldquo;do nothing.&rdquo; It means the order of
        operations matters: decide how much residual waste you will actually
        have in 2040 <em>before</em> committing to a facility sized for the
        waste of 2025.<SourceLink n={4} />
      </p>
    </div>

    <SourceList sources={sources} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
